04275nam a22005775i 9780292768987DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211992txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927689877 a10.7560/7653202doi  a(DE-B1597)588803  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLAN0000002bisacsh1 aKoike, Dale April, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLanguage and Social Relationship in Brazilian Portuguese :bThe Pragmatics of Politeness /cDale April Koike. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (188 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1 Pragmatics and Speech Acts: An Overview -- tChapter 2 Politeness as a Social Phenomenon -- tChapter 3 A Pragmatic Hierarchy of Politeness in Directives -- tChapter 4 Deixis and the Pragmatic Hierarchy of Politeness -- tChapter 5 The Acquisition of Strategies for Politeness -- tChapter 6 Further Explorations in the Study of Directive Speech Acts -- tAppendix Test for Speech Act Comprehension -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Give me the salt" and "Please pass the salt" make the same request, but in a polite situation the first utterance may give offense, while the second may not. How and why such differences in wording and intonation, in a particular context, produce different effects is the concern of pragmatics, the area of linguistics that deals with how speech is used in interaction. In this innovative study of pragmatics in Brazilian Portuguese, Dale Koike analyzes the politeness phenomenon, specifically in the context of speech acts known as "directives." As acts intended to get someone to do something, directives bring into play a variety of sociocultural factors, depending on the relationship between the participants. Using empirical data obtained through natural language observation and from questionnaires of over one hundred adult native speakers, Koike identifies factors—such as age, education, and gender—that influence the strategies of politeness a given speaker is likely to use in making a directive. This research clarifies the unwritten language rules and assumptions that native speakers intuitively follow in phrasing their directive utterances. Koike also includes important material on the acquisition of strategies for politeness by children and adult second-language learners, as well as on gender differences in politeness forms. Her research proposes important additions to the theory of speech acts as conceived by Austin and Searle, particularly in the application of deictic organization to account for a hierarchy of pragmatic forms. Language and Social Relationship in Brazilian Portuguese will be of interest to a wide audience in diverse fields, including linguistics, anthropology, interaction analysis, communications, semantics, sociology, psychology, and education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76532040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292768987423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292768987/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK